WHMurray@DOCKMASTER.NCSC.MIL writes:
> 
> I find this whole situation Kafkaesque.  While it is possible that the
> government believes that this issue is sufficiently important that they
> are forced to act, that is unlikely.  While it is possible that they
> believe that they can get a conviction on narrow grounds, without ever
> considering the constitutional issues, that is equally unlikely.  
> I suppose that, as David Sternlight suggests, the government genuinely
> believes their rules to be "reasonable;"  that those of us who consider 
> them to be arbitrary and capricious are "wrong headed."  We simply 
> need to be "enlightened." (Afterall, David Sternlight thinks they are
> reasonable.)  It is possible that the government would simply like to 
> have these issues aired and clarified; again, very unlikely.  Perhaps 
> it is simply a tactical blunder; bureaucracies are prone to these.  
> 
> The government, under the enlightened leadership of NSA, has been 
> scrupulous in the past in keeping these issues in the executive and
> never letting them come  before the courts or the legislature.  In
> the past they have relied upon appeals to patriotism and national
> security.  When these have failed, and they rarely have, they may
> have resorted to lies, intimidation, or subornation.  
> 
> For example, they have recently paid AT&T US$10 million to prevent them
> from offering a cheap DES-based voice-crypto box.  They could get
> their way with ViaCrypt and Austin Code Works simply by buying them
> (off).
> 
> Never, ever, have they resorted to the ordinary legal process.
> 
> The only way that I can rationalize in my own mind what is happening is
> that there is a rogue in the government.  Someone, or perhaps some
> whole department, is not with the program.  They may not understand it;
> more likely.  They may be resisting it; less likely and a very dangerous
> game.
> 
